\f0\b\fs30 \ul About StarfishX\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\ql\qnatural

\f2\b0\fs24 \cf0 \ulnone StarfishX is a Mac OS X-native application which generates cool desktop patterns. It is based on 
\f1 Mars Saxman's Starfish
\f2 \cf2  \cf0 pattern generation engine. The following are a few of the highlights of StarfishX: \
\
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\ql\qnatural

\f1 \cf0 \'a5 Mac OS X native cocoa application.\
\'a5 Altivec-enabled and multi-threaded to take full advantage of today's dual (and single) processor G4 PowerMacs. (There is also a version of Starfish X which will run on a G3 Macintosh, although it's 
\f0\b much
\f1\b0  slower).\
\'a5 Support for multiple monitors (you can generate a different pattern for each monitor connected to your computer).\
\'a5 Support for both TIFF and JPEG image files.\
\'a5 Option to quit StarfishX when all patterns have been generated. (Perfect for use as a startup item!)\
\'a5 Keeps track of recently-created patterns so you can go back to that really cool pattern StarfishX created yesterday.\
\

\f0\b\fs30 \ul System Requirements\

\f1\b0\fs24 \ulnone \'a5 Any Macintosh running Mac OS X 10.2 or later.\
\'a5 The Altivec-enabled version of StarfishX requires a Macintosh with a G4 or later processor.\
\'a5 StarfishX-G3 will run on any Macintosh which supports Mac OS X 10.2, but it will run 
\f0\b much
\f1\b0  slower than the Altivec-enabled version.\
\'a5 About 1MB of hard disk space for the application, and upwards of 5MB of hard disk space for each full-screen TIFF image. (This is why there's an option to use JPEG images, and smaller patterns use significantly less disk space.)\
\

\f0\b\fs30 \ul How to use StarfishX\

\f1\b0\fs24 \ulnone It's fairly straightforward, but I'll try to give a brief overview of what each option does.\
\

\f0\b\fs30 \ul Settings (left) drawer
\fs26 \ul :
\f1\b0\fs24 \ul \
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\ql\qnatural

\f0\b \cf0 \ulnone Pattern size:
\f1\b0  Pretty self-explanatory. "Small" patterns range from 64x64 pixels to about 1/16th the size of the monitor. "Medium" patterns range from 1/8th to 1/4th of the size of the screen. "Large" patterns range from 1/4 to 1/2 the size of the screen. "Full-screen" is exactly what it suggests. "Random" picks a "small," "medium," "large," or "full-screen" size. "Random (no full-screen)" picks only from "small," "medium," or "large"\'d1useful for generating random patterns which don't take too long to generate or too much disk space. You may also specify a fixed size of your own by selecting the "Custom Size\'c9" option. Custom sizes must be between 16x16 and 9999x9999. Be prepared to wait all day (or even all week!) to generate a 9999x9999 pattern. Note that when you use the Velocity Engine (Altivec)-optimized generator, the width of the pattern will automatically be rounded down to an even multiple of 4.\
\

\f0\b Palette: 
\f1\b0 Tells Starfish what colors to use when generating the pattern. "Full spectrum" picks colors at random from the entire RGB color space. "Random" picks from any of the listed palettes and "full spectrum." "Random (no full spectrum) picks only from the listed palettes. The other palettes attempt to use descriptive names for the colors that will be used. If you select the "Edit..." item from this menu, a sheet will drop down out of the main window which will let you edit the palettes StarfishX uses. See the section "Editing Palettes," below.\
\

\f0\b Arrange:
\f1\b0  This option is used to tell the Desktop System Preference pane how to arrange the pattern on the desktop. These options correspond directly to the same-named options in the Desktop System Preference pane.\
\

\f0\b For:
\f1\b0  Which monitor(s) to generate patterns for. "All screens" will generate a different pattern for each monitor connected to your computer. Otherwise, pick the display which will receive the generated pattern.\
\

\f0\b Random Seed:
\f1\b0  This section lets you specify how the random numbers StarfishX uses are seeded. The "seed" for random numbers determine which numbers are generated and in what order. When given the same seed, the random number generator used by StarfishX will generate the same sequence of numbers, thereby generating the same pattern (provided you use the same non-random settings). The "sequential" and "random" seed options will have StarfishX create a unique pattern each time, whereas the "Use constant seed value" option will cause StarfishX to use the same seed value for all subsequent patterns created. This option is useful when you wish to experiment with a different pattern size or palette but keep the same underlying patterns. Note that you can enter a new seed value at any time, regardless of the setting of the radio buttons here and StarfishX will use that seed value for the next pattern it creates. The "sequential", "random", and "constant" options describe what happens to this seed value 
\f0\b after
\f1\b0  StarfishX has finished creating a new pattern.\
\
(See the FAQ section for more information on how this whole Random Seed stuff works.)\

\f0\b\fs26 \ul \
