\f0\b\fs26 \cf0 \ul Automatic:
\f1\b0\fs24 \ul \

\f0\b \ulnone Create new pattern when StarfishX starts:
\f1\b0  This tells StarfishX to automatically begin generating patterns when it runs. Otherwise, it will wait for you to press the New Pattern button. Useful when you want to use StarfishX to generate new desktop patterns when you first login.\
\

\f0\b Create new pattern on wake from sleep:
\f1\b0  This tells StarfishX to automatically begin generating patterns when your computer wakes from sleep. This option will only work if you left StarfishX running when your computer went to sleep.\
\

\f0\b Generate a new pattern every N minutes/hours/days/weeks:
\f1\b0  You can use this option to tell StarfishX to automatically generate new desktop patterns at the selected time interval. You can optionally select the "Minimize while waiting" option to have StarfishX minimize its window to the dock while it's waiting for the time to generate a new pattern. The window will automatically de-minimize when it is time to generate a new pattern. If you want StarfishX to always minimize its main window (even while it's generating new patterns), minimize the StarfishX window (just like you would any other window in Mac OS X) and 
\f4\i deselect 
\f1\i0 the "Minimize while waiting" option.\
\

\f0\b Quit when pattern creation complete:
\f1\b0  Exactly what it says. StarfishX will quit when it has finished generating patterns for all specified monitors. This option can't be used in conjunction with the "Generate a new pattern every N minutes/hours/days/weeks" option (below).\
\

\f0\b\fs26 \ul Updates:
\f1\b0\fs24 \ulnone \

\f0\b Check for newer version at startup:
\f1\b0  Turn on this option to have StarfishX check its website ( http://homepage.mac.com/mscott/ ) for a newer version every time it starts up. This check requires an active internet connection (otherwise it does nothing). This option causes StarfishX to read a very small file from its website and compare the version information found there with the version of StarfishX you are running.\
\
StarfishX sends no personally-identifiable information when requesting this file. However, since this website is run by Apple Computer and not me, Apple will undoubtedly log your IP address and possibly some other information (the same information they would have logged if you downloaded StarfishX from its homepage). I (the developer of StarfishX) have no access to this information and have no desire to track you in any way. However, I can't guarantee what Apple Computer might do with this information (although I highly doubt there's anything sensitive in what they log). So if you're 
\f4\i really
\f1\i0  paranoid, you can turn this option off.\
\
StarfishX will ask you if you want to enable version checking the first time you run it on your computer. After than, you can always change your mind at any time by returning to the Advanced tab and changing this option.\
\

\f0\b Check Now:
\f1\b0  Click this button to have StarfishX check its website immediately for a newer version (as described above). You can use this option at any time (provided you have an internet connection), regardless of the above setting.\
\

\f0\b\fs26 \ul Advanced:
\f1\b0\fs24 \ulnone \

\f0\b File format:
\f1\b0  What kind of image files to generate. "TIFF file (best quality)" will output the generated patterns in a TIFF file with little or no compression. A full-screen pattern at 1280x1024 will take about 5MB of disk space (and probably RAM), but will result in the sharpest image. "JPEG (smaller size)" will output the generated patterns in a JPEG file set to 100% quality. This will reduce the disk space (and possibly RAM) required for the image, at a (potential) slight loss of image quality. This value defaults to "JPEG" because the difference in quality is minute but the difference in file size is substantial (on the order of 1/5th to 1/10th the TIFF file size).\

\f0\b \
Quality:
\f1\b0  If the "File format:" popup menu is set to JPEG, this slider specifies the quality of the final image. Higher values result in sharper images which use more disk space. Lower values result in images that use less disk space, but at reduced quality. Any value less than 80-90% is probably going to look bad. This option is disabled if the "File format:" popup menu is set to TIFF, since it does not apply to TIFF images.\
\

\f0\b Use multiple processors:
\f1\b0  When this option is enabled, StarfishX will divide the work of generating each pattern amongst the available processors. On a dual processor Mac, this will generate desktop patterns nearly twice as fast (at the expense of other system operations, in some cases). If your machine has more than one processor, this option will be enabled by default. If your machine only has one processor, this option will be disabled.\
\

\f0\b Use Velocity Engine (Altivec):
\f1\b0  This option tells StarfishX whether or not to use the vector processor on a G4 or later to accelerate pattern generation. If your machine has a processor which supports Altivec (basically a G4 or later), this option will be enabled by default. If your machine does not support Altivec (i.e., G3 Macintoshes), this option will be disabled.\
\
The above two options are really available so you can see the difference Altivec and multiple processors makes. If you have a dual processor G4 and turn these two options off, you can get a feeling for what it's like to run StarfishX on a similarly-clocked G3 machine. :-)\
\

\f0\b Run at reduced priority:
\f1\b0  Enable this option to have StarfishX run at the lowest possible priority. All this really means is that if some other process needs the processor, StarfishX will not hog the CPU. This will make your computer more responsive if you are trying to do other things while StarfishX is creating a pattern. Turning this option off will give more time to StarfishX when other applications are using the CPU. Because OS X uses preemptive multitasking and most OS X applications are good about not using the CPU when they're not actually doing anything, leaving this option turned on will not actually slow down pattern generation on an otherwise idle machine. Note that turning this option off requires that you quit and restart StarfishX before it takes effect (although it takes effect immediately when you turn it on). The default is to run at reduced priority. \
\
